The lymphatic system is a circulatory system that works in tandem with our blood. Lymphatic vessels act like a giant drainage system for the body that needs to stay clear for it to work properly. Just like in your home, if the drains are clogged and you can’t get rid of waste effectively—the same is true for your body. The lymphatic system does not have a built-in pump like the heart. So extracting the gunk and getting rid of waste and toxin buildup, which weakens immunity and can lead to various other health issues, is in part up to you!

The lymphatic system relies on the contraction of muscles and joints to move the lymph, so this means taking measures to tense and relax, like dry brushing, massaging, and even laughing!

Learn more about the lymph system and steps you can take to keep it healthy, here: https://bit.ly/2qLGEkv

Blue light is a type of light that is emitted from both the sun and our electronic devices. For biological reasons, our body uses blue light from the sun to keep our circadian rhythms in check and let us know when it’s appropriate to fall asleep and stay awake.

Unfortunately, if you’re someone who uses your phone, computer, or TV screen after the sun sets, you’re effectively telling your body that it’s still daytime, even if it’s midnight and you should be preparing for sleep!

Obviously, this can get in the way of your sleep hygiene, which means that blue lights should be avoided at least two hours before bedtime.

We’ve all been told that drinking water is important, but have you ever thought about why? 

Fluids carry nutrients to your cells, flush bacteria from your bladder, and prevent constipation. Flushing water through your system doesn’t only keep it clean, it also keeps your joints lubricated and working properly. 

As we age, we don’t sense thirst as easily as we once did. This is especially a problem for people on medication that might cause fluid loss. Watch for warning signs of dehydration such as weakness, low blood pressure, dizziness, confusion, or urine that’s dark in color. 

To avoid dehydration, drink 30-50 ounces of water per day (about 1 to 1.5 liters). If you’re feeling sick or sweating a lot, drink even more and eat water-rich foods like salad, fresh fruits, and applesauce.

SAD is a form of depression connected to fatigue, decreased cognitive ability, moodiness, and social withdrawal. Up to 20 percent of people experience SAD, and it often affects women more frequently than men.

The main trigger of SAD is lack of sunlight. When sunlight enters our eyes, it activates the neurotransmitters serotonin and dopamine, the hormones that make us feel happy. Less sunlight = less happiness. 

If you’re not lucky enough to live in a place with year-round sunlight, try these tips:

-Get your vitamin D levels checked. Many of us don’t get enough.

-Nix the sugar. It temporarily boosts our serotonin levels, but the crash leaves us worse off than we were to start with.

-Research shows that B12 deficiency is associated with depression. Get your levels checked, and add more B12-rich foods into your diet, like salmon, eggs, and yogurt.

-Eat the chocolate. Not just any candy bar, I’m talking high-quality, pure cocoa. The good stuff is packed with antioxidants and can enhance a positive mood.

-Tumeric - everyone’s obsessed with it for a reason. Studies have shown that it can help with depression, and its also known for its anti-inflammatory properties, a win-win! Take it with fats (like coconut oil) so that it gets easily absorbed into the bloodstream through the lymphatic system.

-Shine some light. A simple halogen work lamp will do. Sit in its light as you wake up in the morning.

-Create a sleep routine that lets you see as much sun as possible. Go to bed before 11 p.m., avoid caffeine after dinner time, and ditch the bright screens for a book before bed.

As we age, our bodies don’t work the same way that they used to. But don’t worry! You can hack into your system with supplements to keep everything running as it always has. Start with these five:

-Vitamin C: This one helps with hormones. If you’re having trouble staying calm and find yourself getting frazzled or angry a lot, you might be deficient. Talk to your doctor or pharmacist about taking a supplement. 

-Magnesium: This one is extra important if you’re a woman over 35 dealing with PMS. Magnesium helps alleviate muscle spasms, i.e. period cramps. 

-Vitamin D: You reach your peak bone mass around age 30, after that, calcium is super important. Vitamin D helps your body absorb calcium. It also keeps your skin from getting dry and is a good supplement for anyone who is post-menopausal. 

-Omega-3: This stuff lowers stress hormones and reduces inflammation, which is the root of many diseases. Unless you eat fish every day, consider an omega-3 supplement.

-Selenium: This one helps regulate the thyroid, which has a tendency to become more unpredictable and persnickety as you age. Conveniently, one of the best ways to get your selenium is by eating two Brazil nuts per day. That’s all!

SPF stands for Sun Protection Factor and refers to how well a sunscreen can protect against UVB rays, which cause burning and skin cancer. It could be helpful to think of UVB for “burning.” Another type of radiation, called UVA, is responsible for age spots and wrinkles, as well as some types of skin cancers.
Choose sunscreens that are labeled “broad spectrum” to ensure that it protects from both UVA and UVB.

Currently, there is no standard in the United States for listing UVA blocking power. In certain European and Asian countries, UVA protection must be listed on packaging the same way SPF would be.

It’s a common misconception that darker complexions don’t need sunscreen.
